04571nmm a2200661Ia 9780801461552DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014615527 a10.7591/97808014615522doi  a(DE-B1597)515561  a(OCoLC)1083569858  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJS431b.C645 2010eb04a320.8/50974090342221 aConnolly, James J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Elusive Unity :bUrban Democracy and Machine Politics in Industrializing America /cJames J. Connolly. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b15 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough many observers have assumed that pluralism prevailed in American political life from the start, inherited ideals of civic virtue and moral unity proved stubbornly persistent and influential. The tension between these conceptions of public life was especially evident in the young nation's burgeoning cities. Exploiting a wide range of sources, including novels, cartoons, memoirs, and journalistic accounts, James J. Connolly traces efforts to reconcile democracy and diversity in the industrializing cities of the United States from the antebellum period through the Progressive Era.The necessity of redesigning civic institutions and practices to suit city life triggered enduring disagreements centered on what came to be called machine politics. Featuring plebian leadership, a sharp masculinity, party discipline, and frank acknowledgment of social differences, this new political formula first arose in eastern cities during the mid-nineteenth century and became a subject of national discussion after the Civil War. During the Gilded Age and Progressive Era, business leaders, workers, and women proposed alternative understandings of how urban democracy might work. Some tried to create venues for deliberation that built common ground among citizens of all classes, faiths, ethnicities, and political persuasions. But accommodating such differences proved difficult, and a vision of politics as the businesslike management of a contentious modern society took precedence. As Connolly makes clear, machine politics offered at best a quasi-democratic way to organize urban public life. Where unity proved elusive, machine politics provided a viable, if imperfect, alternative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural pluralismzMiddle WestxHistoryy19th century. 0aCultural pluralismzNortheastern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aDemocracyzMiddle WestxHistoryy19th century. 0aDemocracyzNortheastern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMunicipal governmentzMiddle WestxHistoryy19th century. 0aMunicipal governmentzNortheastern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical culturezMiddle WestxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical culturezNortheastern StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 4aUrban Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146155240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801461552423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801461552/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles